	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
	
			<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
			I disagree with Syas, this is an excellent weapon at low levels and well worth the 2plat to upgrade from the short sword you start with. Remember that a delay difference of 4 between 24 and 28 is a lot more significant than the same delay difference between 36 and 40, because of the way you divide damage by delay. The low delay means you hit a lot more often, which makes getting the attention of moving mobs, and finishing off ones that run, much easier. Plus I believe the more often you try to hit, the more quickly your skills go up, so you improve your 1h slash that much more quickly. Which in turn translates to a better chance of success each time you try to hit the mob, and since because of the lower delay you're attempting to hit more often, you do more damage than the pure damage / delay calculation suggests until your 1H slash is maxed out.<BR>
<BR>
And don't forget that at low levels 2-3 plat is a lot of money - it'll buy you a pretty complete set of patchwork armour or even a couple of bits of leather. For 5 plat you'll be much more balanced with a shortsword and a complete set of patchwork that a mino axe and a few bits of cloth.<BR>
<BR>
There's also the role playing point of view - I'm a high elf Paladin and I just can't see myself with a clumsy, heavy, slow axe, no matter how much damage it might do. That's just my opinion, of course, and a dwarven paladin with a mino axe would work just fine.<BR>
<BR>
I can easily see myself sticking with my shortsword for a good few levels yet, and even then I'd choose a long sword over a mino axe, again because of the delay. And I'll defintely do the quest for the Falchion in Felwithe, a delay 24 damage 6 magic weapon will beat a combine long word hands down (and gettin it is a lot more fun). Like most things in EQ it's balanced and never as simple as &quot;this weapon is better than that&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Anyar, High Elf Paladin of Quellious
			</font>
	
		</td>
